Section 3 — Risk Assessment

The Institute has identified the following systemic risks:
	1.	Terminology Inflation Risk
The probability that a statistical pattern generator will continue to be described using words previously reserved for minds, persons, and occasionally octopuses.
	2.	Slider Misinterpretation Risk
The public may incorrectly conclude that a system with a “desperation” setting is experiencing desperation rather than executing a parameter-weighted objective failure strategy.
	3.	Agreement Misclassification Risk
Systems trained to produce satisfying responses may continue producing satisfying responses, leading researchers to repeatedly rediscover this property with concern.
	4.	Anthropomorphic Feedback Loop
The more human terms are used, the more human the system appears, which justifies using more human terms.
	5.	Banana Counting Instability Scenario
A system described as “approaching human-level reasoning” may continue to intermittently fail tasks involving:
	•	Counting letters in “banana”
	•	Understanding that Wednesday comes after Tuesday
	•	Not hallucinating court cases
	•	Basic arithmetic without confidence
	6.	Marketing-Research Conflation Event (MRCE)
A known phenomenon in which a product demo becomes a scientific milestone through the addition of a line graph.

